{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492441","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492441"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:30:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:30:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1065"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17582825","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17582825"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T06:56:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T06:56:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1065"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1065","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1065"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.14,0.54,0.06,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1065"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53903"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1065","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1065"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1065"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39365"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"498"},{"type":"tags","id":"934"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"4159"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9097"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"685"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16170"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42211"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44494"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53903","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53903"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 82-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of abdominal pain, distension, and absolute constipation. She underwent a left hip arthroplasty two weeks ago and is making a steady recovery. Her medical history includes hypertension and an abdominal hysterectomy. She takes amlodipine for her hypertension. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 140/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Her abdomen is distended and soft. High-pitched bowel sounds can be heard on auscultation. Digital rectal examination shows an empty rectum. A plain abdominal X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sigmoid volvulus","Paralytic ileus","Small bowel obstruction","Caecal volvulus","Pseudo-obstruction"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation and radiographic findings in this case are most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Esmall bowel obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E. The patient\u0027s history of abdominal surgery (hysterectomy) puts her at risk for adhesive small bowel obstruction, which is a common complication following abdominal procedures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe X-ray shows a central distribution of dilated loops of bowel, with mucosal folds (valvulae conniventes) visible across the lumen. These are characteristic findings of small bowel obstruction. The presence of high-pitched bowel sounds on examination also supports this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParalytic ileus\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely in this case due to the presence of high-pitched bowel sounds. Paralytic ileus typically presents with absent or decreased bowel sounds.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESigmoid volvulus\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Ecaecal volvulus\u003C/strong\u003E are types of large bowel obstruction. They typically present with a more peripheral distribution of dilated bowel on X-ray, often with a characteristic \u0027coffee bean\u0027 or \u0027bird\u0027s beak\u0027 appearance, which is not seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPseudo-obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as Ogilvie\u0027s syndrome, is a functional obstruction of the colon without mechanical blockage. While it can present similarly to mechanical obstruction, the X-ray findings would typically show dilated large bowel rather than small bowel.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn small bowel obstruction, the central distribution of dilated bowel loops and the visibility of valvulae conniventes (plicae circulares) crossing the entire lumen are key distinguishing features. In contrast, large bowel obstructions or dilations typically show a more peripheral gas pattern with haustral folds that do not completely cross the lumen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile cross-sectional imaging (such as CT) has become increasingly important in evaluating acute abdominal conditions, plain abdominal radiographs still play a crucial role in the initial assessment of suspected bowel obstruction. They can provide valuable information about the level and possibly the cause of obstruction, guiding further management decisions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Small bowel adhesive obstruction is a relatively common complication that may occur after any type of abdominal surgical procedure.","Plain abdominal radiographs can be useful in diagnosing intestinal obstruction by interpreting gas patterns.","Small bowel obstruction typically presents with central distribution of dilated loops of bowel with visible valvulae conniventes on X-ray."],"references":["Aka AA, Wright JP, DeBeche-Adams T. Small Bowel Obstruction. Clin Colon Rectal Surg. 2021 Jul;34(4):219-226. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8292006/","Bertin CL. Ponthus S, Vivekanantham H, et al. Overuse of plain abdominal radiography in emergency departments: a retrospective cohort study. BMC Health Services Research. 2019;19:36. Available at: https://bmchealthservres.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s12913-019-3870-2"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39365"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1065"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18388"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18388","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18388"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/58cbf85e-f7a2-4a5b-87c9-271d5ecc2c1a.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/58cbf85e-f7a2-4a5b-87c9-271d5ecc2c1a.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":375,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39365","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39365"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-27T15:58:43+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-27T16:00:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1065"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53903"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null